definition.value: A benzoic acid carrying at least one sulfanyl substituent.
Conjugate base of thiosalicylic acid.
Conjugate base of 5-chlorosalicylic acid.
Cinchonan or its (8S)-epimer.
The (8S)-epimer of cinchonan.
A substance used as an indicator  of a biological state.
The dianion of balsalazide.
Nonaethylene glycol in which one of the hydroxy groups is substituted by methoxy.

A synthetic peptide of 20 amino acids, comprising D-Phe, Pro, Arg, Pro, Gly, Gly, Gly, Gly, Asn, Gly, Asp, Phe, Glu, Glu, Ile, Pro, Glu, Glu, Tyr, and Leu in sequence. A congener of hirudin (a naturally occurring drug found in the saliva of the medicinal leech), it a specific and reversible inhibitor of thrombin, and is used as an anticoagulant.
Any substance capable of eliciting an immune response only when attached to a large carrier such as a protein. Examples include dinitrophenols; oligosaccharides; peptides; and heavy metals.
The anion formed by deprotonating bromfenac at the carboxyl proton.
A  tertiary amino compound that is the 4-bromobenzhydryl ether of 2-(dimethylamino)ethanol. An antihistamine with antimicrobial properties, it is used in the control of cutaneous allergies.
The hydrochloride salt of bromazine. An antihistamine with antimicrobial properties, it is used in the control of cutaneous allergies.
The monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxy groups of (2xi)-D-gluco-heptonic acid.
An unspecified mixture of (2R)- and 2(S)-D-gluco-heptonic acid.
Any fatty acid whose skeletal carbon atoms form an unbranched open chain.
A fatty acid anion formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid functional group of a straight-chain fatty acid.
The anion formed by deprotonating carboprost at the carboxyl proton.
The anion of cephapirin obtained by removal of a proton form the carboxylic acid group.

A decapeptide comprising 5-oxoprolyl, glutamyl, aspartyl, O-sulfotyrosyl, threonyl, glycyl, tryptopyl, methionyl, aspartyl and phenylalaninamide residues in sequence. Found in the skins of certain Australian amphibians, it is an analogue of the gastrointestinal peptide hormone cholecystokinin and stimulates gastric, biliary, and pancreatic secretion. It is used in cases of paralysis of the intestine (paralytic ileus) and as a diagnostic aid in pancreatic malfunction.

A tetracyclic diterpenoid that is 1a,2,5,5a,6,9,10,10a-octahydro-1H-2,8a-methanocyclopenta[a]cyclopropa[e][10]annulen-11-one substituted at positions 5, 5a and 6 by hydroxy groups, positions 1, 1, 7 and 9 by methyl groups, position 4 by a hydroxymethyl group and position 1 by an oxo group (the 1aR,2S,5R,5aR,6S,8aS,9R,10aR diastereomer).
The diethylamine salt of ceruletide.

A synthetic ten-membered oligopeptide comprising N-acetyl-3-(naphthalen-2-yl)-D-alanyl, 4-chloro-D-phenylalanyl, 3-(pyridin-3-yl)-D-alanyl, L-seryl, L-tyrosyl, N(5)-carbamoyl-D-ornithyl, L-leucyl, L-arginyl, L-prolyl, and D-alaninamide residues coupled in sequence. A gonadotrophin-releasing hormone (GnRH) antagonist, it is used for treatment of infertility and of hormone-sensitive cancers of the prostate and breast.
A chemical substance which inhibits the function of gonadotrophin-releasing hormone (GnRH).
Any salt prepared using acetic acid as the acid component.
Any fatty acid containing anywhere in its structure a ring of atoms.
Any EC 3.4.* (hydrolases acting on peptide bond) inhibitor that inhibits the activity of a serine endopeptidase (EC 3.4.21.*).
The (R)-enantiomer of betaxolol.
The (S)-enantiomer of betaxolol.
A pentasaccharide derivative having one or more substituted or unsubstituted amino groups in place of hydroxy groups at unspecified positions.

The (pharmacologically active) (S)-(+)-enantiomer of brompheniramine. A histamine H1 receptor antagonist, it is used (commonly as its maleate salt) for the symptomatic relief of allergic conditions, including rhinitis and conjunctivitis.
A compound that exhibits agonist activity at the kappa-opioid receptor.
Any compound that exhibits antagonist activity at the delta-opioid receptor.

An EC 1.14.13.* (oxidoreductase acting on paired donors, incorporating 1 atom of oxygen, with NADH or NADPH as one donor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of squalene monooxygenase (EC 1.14.13.132).
An  EC 4.1.1.* (carboxy-lyase) inhibitor that interferes with the action of aromatic-L-amino-acid decarboxylase (EC 4.1.1.28).
A prostanoid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any prostaglandin.

A broad spectrum, third-generation cephalosporin antibiotic with (Z)-2-(4-methyl-1,3-thiazol-5-yl)ethenyl and (2Z)-2-(2-amino-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)-2-(methoxyimino)acetamido groups at positions 3 and 7, respectively, of the cephem skeleton. Generally administered as its orally absorbed pivaloyloxymethyl ester prodrug, it is used for the treatment of mild to moderate infections caused by susceptible strains of microorganisms in acute bacterial exacerbation of chronic bronchitis, community-acquired pneumonia, pharyngitis/tonsillitis, and uncomplicated skin and skin-structure infections.
The conjugate acid of cefepime.
The dianion formed by removal of a proton from each of the carboxylic acid groups of cefotetan.
The anion resulting from the removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of cephalexin.
4-Aminobenzoic acid in which one of the hydrogens ortho- to the carboxylic acid group is substituted by chlorine.

A monohydroxyquinoline that is quinolin-8-ol in which the hydrogens at positions 5 and 7 have been substituted by chlorine. A synthetic antibacterial prepared by chlorination of quinolin-8-ol, it is used for the treatment of dandruff and seborrhoeic dermatitis of the scalp.
The dihydrate of the anhydrous form of cidofovir. A nucleoside analogue, it is an injectable antiviral used for the treatment of cytomegalovirus (CMV) retinitis in AIDS patients.
Any EC 3.4.* (hydrolases acting on peptide bond) inhibitor that inhibits the action of a dipeptidase (EC 3.4.13.*).

A monohydroxyquinoline that is quinolin-8-ol in which the hydrogens at positions 5 and 7 are replaced by iodine.  It is considered the drug of choice for treating asymptomatic or moderate forms of amoebiasis.
The anion resulting from the removal of a proton from a carboxylic acid group of cilastatin.
